# TrackerGeoSim

Geant4 simulation of a 2×3 m² tracking detector plane, built using the
GeoModel geometry description toolkit.

---

## Detector layout

```
    Y
    ^
    +1500 ┌──────────────────────────────────────────┐
          │  LEFT tubes  +  RIGHT tubes  (outer top)  │  y = [+200, +1500]
    +200  ├───────────┬──────────────────┬────────────┤
          │ PS tiles  │  central tubes   │  PS tiles  │  y = [-200, +200]
          │ (left)    │  x = [-600,+600] │  (right)   │
    -200  ├───────────┴──────────────────┴────────────┤
          │  LEFT tubes  +  RIGHT tubes  (outer bot)  │  y = [-1500, -200]
    -1500 └──────────────────────────────────────────┘
          -1000  -600                  +600  +1000   --> X  (mm)
```

**Drift tubes** — mylar straws (5 mm diameter, 15 µm wall), ArCO2 70/30 fill,
1.2 m long, running horizontally along X.  Each region uses a double-staggered
layer (two sub-layers separated by one tube radius in Z and half a pitch in Y).

The outer top and bottom bands each contain two independent half-planes:

| Half-plane | X extent | Z centre |
|---|---|---|
| Left  | [−1000, +200] mm | −5 mm |
| Right | [−200, +1000] mm | +5 mm |

The overlap region x = [−200, +200] mm is covered by both half-planes.

**Polystyrene tiles** — 1×1×1 cm³ tiles in two 400×400 mm blocks at
x = [−1000, −600] mm (sector −1) and x = [+600, +1000] mm (sector +1),
both in the y = [−200, +200] mm strip.

---

## Dependencies

| Package | Minimum version | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| CMake | 3.16 | |
| GCC / Clang | GCC 10 / Clang 11 | C++20 required |
| Geant4 | 11.x | Built with `ui_all vis_all` |
| GeoModelCore | 6.x | Provides `GeoModelKernel` |
| GeoModelG4 | 6.x | Provides `GeoModel2G4` bridge |
| ROOT | 6.x | `Core`, `RIO`, `Tree` components |

---

## Building

```bash
# From the project root
mkdir build && cd build

cmake .. \
  -DCMAKE_PREFIX_PATH="/path/to/geant4;/path/to/geomodel;/path/to/root"

make -j$(nproc)
```

If Geant4, GeoModel and ROOT are already on your `CMAKE_PREFIX_PATH` or sourced
via their respective `thisgeant4.sh` / `thisroot.sh` setup scripts, the plain
`cmake ..` is sufficient.

After a successful build the binary is at:

```
build/run_tracker
```

The vis macro `tracker_vis.mac` is copied automatically into the build directory
by CMake.

---

## Running

### Geometry visualisation only

Opens the interactive Geant4 viewer without simulating any particles.

```bash
./run_tracker --visualize
```

Control the level of detail with `--vis-mode`:

| Mode | What is shown |
|---|---|
| `0` | Envelope outlines only (fastest) |
| `1` | Colour-coded by region (default) |
| `2` | Full detail — individual tube walls, gas volumes, tiles |

```bash
./run_tracker --visualize --vis-mode 2
```

Useful interactive commands inside the viewer:

```
# Face-on view from upstream (+Z direction)
/vis/viewer/set/viewpointThetaPhi 90 0

# Side view
/vis/viewer/set/viewpointThetaPhi 90 90

# Zoom
/vis/viewer/zoomTo 2.0
```

### Export geometry to GDML

```bash
./run_tracker --write-gdml
./run_tracker --write-gdml --gdml-out my_geometry.gdml
```

### Run a simulation

```bash
./run_tracker --n-events 1000
```

This fires 1000 events and writes hits to `tracker_hits.root` (default output
file).  The SD is only registered when `--n-events` is greater than zero, so
vis-only runs remain clean.

### Full option reference

```
--n-events   <N>         Number of events to simulate      (default: 0)
--output     <file>      ROOT output filename               (default: tracker_hits.root)
--seed       <N>         Random seed (0 = Geant4 default)

--particle   <name>      Geant4 particle name               (default: mu-)
--energy-MeV <E>         Kinetic energy [MeV]               (default: 1000)
--pos-mm     <x> <y> <z> Gun position [mm]                  (default: 0 0 -15)
--dir        <x> <y> <z> Direction unit vector              (default: 0 0 1)
--sigma-xy-mm <s>        Gaussian beam spread in X,Y [mm]  (default: 0)

--visualize              Open interactive viewer
--vis-mode   <0|1|2>     Visualisation detail level         (default: 1)
--vis-macro  <file>      Geant4 vis macro to execute        (default: tracker_vis.mac)

--write-gdml             Export geometry to GDML
--gdml-out   <file>      GDML output filename               (default: tracker_geometry.gdml)
```

### Example commands

```bash
# 10 GeV muon along beam axis, 1000 events
./run_tracker --n-events 1000 --particle mu- --energy-MeV 10000

# 5 GeV pion with 2 mm beam spread, custom output file
./run_tracker --n-events 500 --particle pi- --energy-MeV 5000 \
              --sigma-xy-mm 2.0 --output pion_run.root

# Electron from the side (along X), positioned upstream in X
./run_tracker --n-events 100 --particle e- --energy-MeV 1000 \
              --pos-mm -1100 0 0 --dir 1 0 0

# Visualise and export GDML at the same time
./run_tracker --visualize --write-gdml --vis-mode 1

# Fixed seed for reproducible results
./run_tracker --n-events 1000 --seed 42
```

---

## Output file structure

The ROOT file contains a single TTree named `Events` with one row per event.
All branches are `std::vector<T>` — one element per hit within that event.
Events with no hits produce a row with empty vectors.

### Tube hit branches

| Branch | Type | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `tube_trackID` | `vector<int>` | Geant4 track ID |
| `tube_edep` | `vector<double>` | Energy deposit [MeV] |
| `tube_x/y/z` | `vector<double>` | Hit position — centroid of steps [mm] |
| `tube_x/y/z_entry` | `vector<double>` | Track entry point into gas volume [mm] |
| `tube_x/y/z_exit` | `vector<double>` | Track exit point from gas volume [mm] |

### Tile hit branches

| Branch | Type | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `tile_trackID` | `vector<int>` | Geant4 track ID |
| `tile_edep` | `vector<double>` | Energy deposit [MeV] |
| `tile_tileX` | `vector<int>` | Tile column index (0 – 39) |
| `tile_tileY` | `vector<int>` | Tile row index (0 – 39) |
| `tile_sector` | `vector<int>` | −1 = left block, +1 = right block |
| `tile_x/y/z` | `vector<double>` | Hit position [mm] |

### Reading the output — PyROOT example

```python
import uproot

with uproot.open("tracker_hits.root") as f:
    tree = f["Events"]

    for batch in tree.iterate(step_size=100):
        # tube hits
        for edep, x, y, z in zip(batch["tube_edep"],
                                   batch["tube_x"],
                                   batch["tube_y"],
                                   batch["tube_z"]):
            # each of these is an awkward array over one event
            print("tube edep:", edep, "MeV  at x=", x, "y=", y, "z=", z)

        # tile hits
        for edep, tx, ty, sec in zip(batch["tile_edep"],
                                      batch["tile_tileX"],
                                      batch["tile_tileY"],
                                      batch["tile_sector"]):
            print("tile edep:", edep, "MeV  tile=(", tx, ",", ty,
                  ")  sector=", sec)
```

### Reading the output — ROOT macro example

```cpp
void read_hits(const char* fname = "tracker_hits.root") {
    TFile* f = TFile::Open(fname);
    TTree* t = f->Get<TTree>("Events");

    std::vector<double>* tube_edep = nullptr;
    std::vector<double>* tube_x    = nullptr;
    std::vector<int>*    tile_sector = nullptr;
    std::vector<double>* tile_edep   = nullptr;

    t->SetBranchAddress("tube_edep",   &tube_edep);
    t->SetBranchAddress("tube_x",      &tube_x);
    t->SetBranchAddress("tile_sector", &tile_sector);
    t->SetBranchAddress("tile_edep",   &tile_edep);

    for (Long64_t ev = 0; ev < t->GetEntries(); ++ev) {
        t->GetEntry(ev);
        std::cout << "Event " << ev
                  << "  tube hits: " << tube_edep->size()
                  << "  tile hits: " << tile_edep->size() << "\n";
    }
}
```

